of course was:

514
00:29:23,791 --> 00:29:25,687
How to get there
without LSD?

515
00:29:25,804 --> 00:29:28,182
Belly, as you know,
theorized that young children

516
00:29:28,509 --> 00:29:32,277
have the capacity to see
these other worlds naturally.

517
00:29:32,483 --> 00:29:34,024
I know, you already
told me about that.

518
00:29:34,570 --> 00:29:36,384
Bell's experiments
with Cortexiphan.

519
00:29:36,536 --> 00:29:37,060
<i>Yes.</i>

520
00:29:37,111 --> 00:29:38,942
He theorized
that properly nurtured,

521
00:29:39,278 --> 00:29:40,719
these abilities
could be heightened,

522
00:29:40,912 --> 00:29:41,950
intensified,

523
00:29:42,160 --> 00:29:44,723
and that in time,
his subjects may be able

524
00:29:44,758 --> 00:29:47,338
<i>may be able to travel
from here to there.</i>

525
00:29:47,480 --> 00:29:48,414
Over there?

526
00:29:50,024 --> 00:29:51,572
You mean
an alternate world?

527
00:29:56,755 --> 00:29:58,033
Around this time,

528
00:29:58,968 --> 00:30:01,276
something was lost
to me, Peter.

529
00:30:01,866 --> 00:30:03,431
Something precious.

530
00:30:03,994 --> 00:30:08,576
I became convinced that
if only I could cross over myself,

531
00:30:08,896 --> 00:30:12,842
then I could <i>take</i> from there
what I had lost here.

532
00:30:14,119 --> 00:30:14,789
And what was
the plan?

533
00:30:14,839 --> 00:30:15,898
You were just gonna
open up a hole

534
00:30:15,919 --> 00:30:17,310
and then walk over
to the other side?

535
00:30:17,405 --> 00:30:19,928
No...
It's not that simple.

536
00:30:21,289 --> 00:30:23,330
You have to find
the right place first.

537
00:30:24,812 --> 00:30:25,987
<i>Finding the right place</i>

538
00:30:26,033 --> 00:30:27,740
<i>to cross over
is the key.</i>

539
00:30:27,775 --> 00:30:31,886
Dr. Bell once posited
that our world has "soft spots,"

540
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:34,525
<i>places where the fundamental
constants of nature--</i>

541
00:30:34,562 --> 00:30:36,897
The speed of light,
gravity,

542
00:30:37,106 --> 00:30:39,208
The mass of a proton,
for example,

543
00:30:39,396 --> 00:30:40,851
have begun
to decay.

544
00:30:41,859 --> 00:30:44,477
As a result,
in these particular areas,

545
00:30:44,943 --> 00:30:47,683
<i>the membrane between
the realities is thinner,</i>

546
00:30:47,724 --> 00:30:49,004
almost porous.

547
00:30:49,543 --> 00:30:51,935
Well, the Bermuda Triangle
is one,

548
00:30:52,020 --> 00:30:53,027
<i>but there are others.</i>

549
00:30:53,062 --> 00:30:54,210
<i>And until recently,</i>

550
00:30:54,408 --> 00:30:56,695
these areas
were extremely rare.

551
00:30:57,396 --> 00:30:58,584
What do you mean
"until recently"?

552
00:30:58,640 --> 00:30:59,432
What happened?

553
00:30:59,622 --> 00:31:01,385
We happened,
Agent Dunham.

554
00:31:01,863 --> 00:31:04,236
Scientific progress,
advancing technologies.

555
00:31:04,330 --> 00:31:06,197
By meddling
with the laws of nature,

556
00:31:06,228 --> 00:31:09,238
has hastened the decay
of these constant fundamentals

557
00:31:09,292 --> 00:31:11,781
and increased
the number of soft spots.

558
00:31:12,314 --> 00:31:13,832
So you're suggesting
Jones is looking

559
00:31:13,868 --> 00:31:15,043
for one of these
soft spots.

560
00:31:15,094 --> 00:31:15,762
Yes.

561
00:31:16,110 --> 00:31:18,845
In the belief that by releasing
the right kind of energy,

562
00:31:19,259 --> 00:31:22,119
and aiming it exactly
at the proper spot,

563
00:31:23,108 --> 00:31:25,107
he could effectively
break through.

564
00:31:25,876 --> 00:31:27,101
<i>Of course,
there's a problem</i>

565
00:31:27,208 --> 00:31:28,898
<i>opening a hole
to another reality.</i>

566
00:31:29,159 --> 00:31:33,745
In theory, that would
also allow things from there

567
00:31:33,848 --> 00:31:35,502
to pass over here,

568
00:31:37,198 --> 00:31:39,001
which could be
dangerous.

569
00:31:40,138 --> 00:31:43,680
And so,
I also built a plug.

570
00:31:44,142 --> 00:31:45,046
A plug?

571
00:31:45,303 --> 00:31:47,477
Actually,
more a patch

572
00:31:49,202 --> 00:31:51,827
to close the hole
should the need ever arise.

573
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:53,326
This is that patch,
Peter.

574
00:31:53,420 --> 00:31:54,599
This is
what I had to find.

575
00:31:54,634 --> 00:31:55,902
Okay,
just so I'm clear.

576
00:31:56,732 --> 00:32:00,363
Somewhere out there, there is
a hole to another reality,

577
00:32:00,373 --> 00:32:01,496
and you need
to plug it?

578
00:32:01,545 --> 00:32:02,613
Yes,
I'm afraid so.

579
00:32:02,798 --> 00:32:04,373
Well, do you know
where it is?

580
00:32:04,923 --> 00:32:05,740
Yes.

581
00:32:06,762 --> 00:32:07,767
Yes,
I do, Peter.

582
00:32:09,308 --> 00:32:10,977
Reiden.
Reiden Lake.

583
00:32:11,393 --> 00:32:13,209
<i>We have to identify
another soft spot,</i>

584
00:32:13,275 --> 00:32:14,643
then we'll know
where he's going.

585
00:32:14,702 --> 00:32:16,295
We should expand
the search perimeters.

586
00:32:16,454 --> 00:32:18,338
Did you map events
beyond the eastern seaboard?

587
00:32:18,582 --> 00:32:19,767
No,
they're not in our database.

588
00:32:19,802 --> 00:32:20,601
I'll call my office

589
00:32:20,636 --> 00:32:22,412
and have the files
transferred to your system.

590
00:32:22,537 --> 00:32:24,260
Which of these events
are the oldest?

591
00:32:24,477 --> 00:32:25,360
Do you remember?

592
00:32:26,316 --> 00:32:28,848
I mean,
these events are somehow

593
00:32:28,853 --> 00:32:30,862
consequences
of soft spots--

594
00:32:31,022 --> 00:32:31,580
Well...

595
00:32:33,206 --> 00:32:35,045
These are
the first recorded incidents.

596
00:32:36,050 --> 00:32:38,162
They all go back
more than 15 years.

597
00:32:38,992 --> 00:32:40,026
Becca's Meadow...

598
00:32:40,166 --> 00:32:41,839
<i>That was the site
of the first incident</i>

599
00:32:41,885 --> 00:32:42,904
<i>we know about.</i>

600
00:32:45,964 --> 00:32:46,787
Wait...

601
00:32:47,964 --> 00:32:50,427
All of these incidents
point to here.

602
00:32:50,745 --> 00:32:51,943
That's where
he's going.

603
00:32:53,396 --> 00:32:54,943
Reiden Lake.

604
00:32:58,870 --> 00:33:01,015
Get all the gear,
get set up.

605
00:33:15,310 --> 00:33:16,155
Come on, men.

606
00:33:16,326 --> 00:33:17,894
We're going
to the other side.

607
00:33:26,110 --> 00:33:28,109
It's just
the other side of the lake.

608
00:33:28,761 --> 00:33:30,483
<i>The place where
I opened the hole.</i>

609
00:33:31,904 --> 00:33:33,501
That's awfully
convenient.

610
00:33:33,892 --> 00:33:35,224
Not convenient
at all.

611
00:33:35,259 --> 00:33:35,942
That's why I bought

612
00:33:35,997 --> 00:33:37,496
the beach house
in the first place.

613
00:33:37,906 --> 00:33:38,796
The proximity.

614
00:33:39,940 --> 00:33:41,577
Come on, Peter.
Can't you go faster?

615
00:33:41,800 --> 00:33:43,106
We may not have
much time.

616
00:33:43,158 --> 00:33:43,907
After all
these years,

617
00:33:43,938 --> 00:33:45,533
what's going to happen
if we're not <i>on</i> time?

618
00:33:45,621 --> 00:33:46,767
I don't know!

619
00:33:47,880 --> 00:33:50,305
But my friend came
and he said we must.

620
00:33:50,521 --> 00:33:52,649
He only comes when
it's of dire consequence.

621
00:33:52,705 --> 00:33:54,023
And what friend
would that be?

622
00:33:54,160 --> 00:33:55,468
The bald one.

623
00:33:56,251 --> 00:33:58,498
You mean the one that
Olivia calls 'The Observer'?

624
00:33:58,545 --> 00:33:59,225
Yes.

625
00:33:59,462 --> 00:34:01,240
The man who attacked me
in the woods.

626
00:34:01,330 --> 00:34:02,799
He must've
had a very good reason.

627
00:34:03,369 --> 00:34:05,084
I'm sure he didn't mean you
any harm.

628
00:34:05,171 --> 00:34:06,974
What else aren't
you telling me, Walter?

629
00:34:07,558 --> 00:34:08,906
Lots,
I'm sure,

630
00:34:09,175 --> 00:34:10,780
but none of it
is relevant.

631
00:34:11,972 --> 00:34:15,354
Can't--it's been so long.
This all looks the same.

632
00:34:15,862 --> 00:34:18,256
Oh...
Peter, Peter, Peter, Peter.

633
00:34:18,312 --> 00:34:18,760
Peter!

634
00:34:18,795 --> 00:34:19,769
<i>Stop it!
Stop!</i>

635
00:34:25,700 --> 00:34:26,624
Okay.

636
00:34:26,860 --> 00:34:27,621
Now what?

637
00:34:38,965 --> 00:34:40,741
That thing's not going
to blow up, is it?

638
00:34:42,431 --> 00:34:43,767
I certainly
hope not.

639
00:34:47,172 --> 00:34:48,123
What?

640
00:34:51,565 --> 00:34:53,223
You may not
remember this.

641
00:34:53,442 --> 00:34:54,349
When you were
a boy,

642
00:34:54,400 --> 00:34:56,102
- you were very sick, dying.
- Walter.

643
00:34:56,258 --> 00:34:57,794
And sometimes,
you got scared.

644
00:34:58,016 --> 00:34:59,944
And to calm yourself,

645
00:35:00,568 --> 00:35:02,098
to forget what you were
going through,

646
00:35:02,174 --> 00:35:04,535
you took
to collecting coins.

647
00:35:06,189 --> 00:35:06,918
This one...

648
00:35:09,670 --> 00:35:10,904
This was
your favorite.

649
00:35:16,363 --> 00:35:17,111
You're right.

650
00:35:18,012 --> 00:35:19,231
I don't remember
any of that.

651
00:35:21,713 --> 00:35:22,907
I do.

652
00:35:26,954 --> 00:35:28,053
Walter!

653
00:35:31,831 --> 00:35:33,137
- It's okay, it's okay.
- Easy, easy.

654
00:35:33,172 --> 00:35:34,531
- Take it easy.
- <i>Hey, they're with me.</i>

655
00:35:34,595 --> 00:35:35,639
- Easy, easy.
- It's okay.

656
00:35:37,324 --> 00:35:38,537
Agent Dunham...

657
00:35:38,771 --> 00:35:39,980
H-How did you know
where we were?

658
00:35:39,996 --> 00:35:41,267
What are you
doing here?

659
00:35:41,413 --> 00:35:43,333
We're trying to plug a hole
in the universe.

660
00:35:43,369 --> 00:35:44,499
What are you
doing here?

661
00:35:45,310 --> 00:35:47,849
- Apparently the same thing.
- But how did you--

662
00:35:49,251 --> 00:35:50,411
<i>Oh no.</i>

663
00:35:52,165 --> 00:35:53,130
What is that?

664
00:36:22,435 --> 00:36:23,769
Dr. Bishop,
stay down.

665
00:36:26,431 --> 00:36:29,094
Keep going please.
Don't stop what you're doing.

666
00:36:29,605 --> 00:36:31,174
<i>Hold them off
as long as you can.</i>

667
00:36:33,503 --> 00:36:34,852
Olivia,
I'll cover you.

668
00:36:38,876 --> 00:36:41,305
Walter!
Hey, Walter, stay here.

669
00:36:41,341 --> 00:36:43,053
They'll need this
to close the portal,

670
00:36:43,102 --> 00:36:44,549
to prevent him
from going over.

671
00:36:44,786 --> 00:36:45,663
Give it to me.
I'll do it.

672
00:36:46,383 --> 00:36:47,582
- Give it to me!
- Okay.

673
00:36:47,605 --> 00:36:48,200
All right.

674
00:36:48,780 --> 00:36:50,429
It's simple,
a child could do it.

675
00:36:50,596 --> 00:36:52,537
You just twist this.

676
00:37:00,649 --> 00:37:01,777
<i>What's the status?</i>

677
00:37:03,501 --> 00:37:05,285
<i>Coordinates
are coming into place, sir.</i>

678
00:37:07,240 --> 00:37:08,688
We're almost there,
sir.

679
00:37:10,495 --> 00:37:11,624
Jones?

680
00:37:17,790 --> 00:37:18,760
Don't move.

681
00:37:19,706 --> 00:37:21,444
Manifold is stable.

682
00:37:21,613 --> 00:37:22,480
Don't move.

683
00:37:29,438 --> 00:37:31,689
Stop!
Don't move.

684
00:37:33,007 --> 00:37:34,256
Beautiful,
isn't it?

685
00:37:36,079 --> 00:37:37,990
<i>You'll understand
if this reunion is brief.</i>

686
00:37:38,062 --> 00:37:40,293
If you take one more step,
I'll shoot.

687
00:37:40,529 --> 00:37:41,957
Goodbye,
Agent Dunham.

688
00:37:42,121 --> 00:37:42,643
Don't!

689
00:37:55,963 --> 00:37:57,133
The teleporter...

690
00:37:58,654 --> 00:38:00,644
It may be killing me,
but in the meantime,

691
00:38:01,825 --> 00:38:04,104
It's made me something
rather special.

692
00:38:04,678 --> 00:38:07,994
<i>You see, your bullets
just go right through me.</i>

693
00:38:08,152 --> 00:38:11,878
And soon Dr. Bell will see
just how special I am.

694
00:38:17,626 --> 00:38:18,826
- Stop!
- Dunham!

695
00:38:51,494 --> 00:38:52,408
Hey.

696
00:38:54,795 --> 00:38:55,592
Hey.

697
00:38:58,647 --> 00:39:00,614
Under normal circumstances,
I would ask you

698
00:39:00,650 --> 00:39:02,037
when I could expect
your report.

699
00:39:03,750 --> 00:39:06,001
But in this case, I find myself
at a bit of a loss.

700
00:39:06,708 --> 00:39:07,929
How is Nina?

701
00:39:08,002 --> 00:39:09,102
She's doing fine.

702
00:39:10,067 --> 00:39:11,853
She wanted me
to convey her gratitude.

703
00:39:16,470 --> 00:39:17,623
What?

704
00:39:18,339 --> 00:39:19,777
We've been told
to cease and desist

705
00:39:19,823 --> 00:39:21,630
our investigation
into William Bell.

706
00:39:21,888 --> 00:39:22,916
By whom?

707
00:39:23,347 --> 00:39:25,155
The kind of people that
when they give you an order,

708
00:39:25,211 --> 00:39:26,383
you don't question it.

709
00:39:29,500 --> 00:39:30,752
I'm sorry.

710
00:39:38,223 --> 00:39:39,272
Dr. Bishop...

711
00:39:39,520 --> 00:39:40,890
Good news.

712
00:39:42,347 --> 00:39:43,990
I got you
some berry boom.

713
00:39:48,099 --> 00:39:48,802
<i>Hey.</i>

714
00:39:49,674 --> 00:39:50,408
What's wrong?

715
00:40:10,078 --> 00:40:11,461
"I'm stepping out
for a bit.

716
00:40:11,892 --> 00:40:14,040
Don't worry about me, son.
I know where I'm going."

717
00:40:16,135 --> 00:40:17,375
You want me
to call the police?

718
00:40:21,663 --> 00:40:22,452
No.

719
00:40:26,206 --> 00:40:28,448
That is the first time
he's ever written a note.

720
00:40:30,334 --> 00:40:32,128
I think our little boy
is growing up.

721
00:41:31,356 --> 00:41:31,962
Hello?

722
00:41:32,265 --> 00:41:34,739
<i>Agent Dunham,
it's Nina Sharp.</i>

723
00:41:34,759 --> 00:41:36,156
<i>You held up
your end of the bargain.</i>

724
00:41:36,194 --> 00:41:37,948
<i>Now,
I'd like to hold up mine.</i>

725
00:41:38,190 --> 00:41:40,001
<i>Would you mind coming
to Manhattan tomorrow?</i>

726
00:41:40,030 --> 00:41:40,786
Sure.

727
00:41:41,130 --> 00:41:43,142
<i>Do you know the Mutsumi Hotel
on Broadway?</i>

728
00:41:43,714 --> 00:41:44,330
Yes.

729
00:41:44,377 --> 00:41:46,249
<i>Great.
Tomorrow it is, then.</i>

730
00:41:46,291 --> 00:41:49,061
<i>I hope you understand
why I can't go through channels.</i>

731
00:41:49,282 --> 00:41:51,481
<i>And I appreciate it
if you didn't tell anyone</i>

732
00:41:51,512 --> 00:41:52,528
<i>about this either.</i>

733
00:41:52,740 --> 00:41:54,832
<i>I don't mean
to sound overly cautious,</i>

734
00:41:54,867 --> 00:41:57,129
<i>but I think
you'll soon understand</i>

735
00:41:57,205 --> 00:41:59,260
<i>why we'll want
to keep this between us.</i>

736
00:41:59,625 --> 00:42:00,919
<i>Let's say 1:00?</i>

737
00:42:01,131 --> 00:42:02,130
<i>Come alone.</i>

738
00:42:02,484 --> 00:42:04,116
<i>I'll answer
any questions you have.</i>

739
00:42:25,759 --> 00:42:26,735
No,
thank you.

740
00:42:43,286 --> 00:42:44,399
Uh, Nina Sharp?

741
00:42:45,788 --> 00:42:47,159
Olivia Dunham.

742
00:42:51,167 --> 00:42:52,656
Uh, no, I don't want
to leave a message.

743
00:42:52,700 --> 00:42:54,085
She's expecting
my call.

744
00:42:57,212 --> 00:42:59,309
What do you mean
she's out of the country?

745
00:43:58,164 --> 00:43:59,540
Agent Dunham,
welcome.

746
00:44:00,859 --> 00:44:01,695
Right this way.

747
00:44:10,650 --> 00:44:11,269
Go right in.

748
00:45:01,831 --> 00:45:04,586
I've been waiting
quite a long time for this.

749
00:45:07,124 --> 00:45:08,163
Where am I?

750
00:45:11,112 --> 00:45:12,138
Who are you?

751
00:45:12,894 --> 00:45:15,309
The answer
to your first question is--

752
00:45:16,320 --> 00:45:18,172
It's very complicated.

753
00:45:19,941 --> 00:45:21,526
The answer
to your second...

754
00:45:23,817 --> 00:45:25,368
I'm William Bell.

